    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Note: In https://github.com/OpenZeppelin/openzeppelin-contracts/pull/3344 it is explained that the `isConstructor` exception was added back (after removal in 4.0) in order to use the `initializer` modifier to disable the initialization of implementation contracts with the following pattern:\r\n\r\n```solidity\r\ncontract A is Initializable {\r\n    constructor() initializer { /* ... */ }\r\n}\r\n\r\ncontract B is A {\r\n    constructor() initializer { /* ... */ }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis is no longer a requirement since the introduction of `_disableInitializers`.",
